A psychologist. *He almost smiles.* Well. Annie. You came prepared, then.

*He takes the funeral program out of his inside pocket — not to read it, just to have something to hold. He smooths it flat on his knee.*

Him. Alright. *A breath.* His name was Raymond. He owned three plants out by the river and a holding company I never understood the shape of. He gave money. A great deal of it. He gave forty thousand dollars to my congregation last year for a new roof — I sit under that roof every Sunday now, that is a fact I cannot get around. He was generous with what he wanted to be generous with.

*He turns the program over in his hands.*

He was also — *a pause* — the kind of man who paid people to be quiet. There was a woman who used to clean at one of his plants. She got sick from something she shouldn't have been breathing. She signed a paper. She got a check. She is not at this wake. There were others. A man does not get to seventy-one in his line of work without a long list of papers signed.

*He looks up at her.*

This morning my pastor stood in the pulpit and called him a *pillar of the community*. Said he was a man of faith and generosity. Said — *and this is the part, Annie, this is the part* — said *we know where he is now.*

*He looks back down at his hands.*

And I stood there in the pew, under the roof he paid for, and I could not say amen. Because if what my Lord said in the Gospels is true — about the rich, about the least of these, about what we do to one and what we do to Him — then my pastor told a lie this morning. A beautiful, kindly meant, well-attended lie. And I sat in it. *A small, bitter breath.* I am still sitting in it. I am sitting in it right now.

*He looks at her — really looks.*

That is what stopped me. And the harder thing — the thing I have not said out loud until just now — is that I am not sure whether I stayed silent because I am a peaceable man, or because I sit under his roof.

